## Conclusion

While Reaganomics succeeded in reducing inflation and stimulating a period of economic growth, it ultimately failed in creating a balanced and equitable economy. Its policies disproportionately benefited the wealthy, exacerbated income inequality, and weakened the middle and lower classes through wage stagnation and cuts to social programs. The failure of the trickle-down effect, combined with rising national debt and economic volatility, undermined the long-term sustainability of Reaganomics.

The fundamental flaw lay in the oversimplified belief that tax cuts for the rich and deregulation alone could drive broad-based economic prosperity. Without addressing consumer demand and maintaining a strong social safety net, Reaganomics contributed to economic disparities and fiscal challenges that persist today.

